# Related Work And Positioning

How {{PROJECT_NAME}} relates to prior work: the axes along which to position it, the concrete comparison targets, and the one difference that matters. This is guidance the {{ROLE_TERM}} applies when writing the related-work section or framing a contribution. Position honestly -- the goal is to locate the work precisely, not to inflate it.

## 1. Positioning Principles

- Position by axis, not by ranking. Say where {{PROJECT_NAME}} sits on a dimension, not that it is "better than" a list of methods.
- Credit prior work for what it does well, then state the specific gap {{PROJECT_NAME}} addresses. A related-work section that only criticizes reads as defensive.
- Compare on conditions you can match. If a prior method used a different dataset or budget, say so rather than implying a head-to-head you did not run.
- Keep every comparative number inside the safe-claim boundary in `docs/writing/paper-writing-guide.md` section 4.

## 2. Positioning Axes

The dimensions along which methods in this area differ. Pick the two or three axes where {{PROJECT_NAME}} has a distinct, defensible position; do not list every axis imaginable. Fill in the list for this project; the items below are worked examples.

- Supervision source (worked example): how a method obtains its training signal -- human labels, programmatic/weak labels, or self-supervision. Place {{PROJECT_NAME}} on that spectrum and name the nearest prior method on each side.
- Cost / compute regime (worked example): the budget a method assumes -- large-scale pretraining, moderate fine-tuning, or low-resource. State which regime {{PROJECT_NAME}} targets, because methods are rarely comparable across regimes.

For each axis, write one sentence locating {{PROJECT_NAME}} relative to the closest prior work on that axis. Reference any supporting numbers from `docs/evaluation/comparison.md`.

